{% comment %}
  Rendered as a block inside sections/main-product.liquid (see the
  `low_stock_alert` case there), positioned via block_order so it sits
  right after price - a "more user friendly location" than the original
  standalone section this replaced, which rendered at the bottom of the
  whole page.

  Visually matches this theme's own native "Inventory" block (same
  dot-icon SVG + amber rgb(238,148,65) it already uses for its own
  low-stock state, main-product.liquid ~line 127) so this reads as part
  of the theme's own design language. The difference: that native block
  reflects Shopify's own inventory_quantity: this one is driven by the
  .NET backend via the App Proxy (GET /apps/inventory/products/by-variant/{id}),
  which is the actual point of this demo - showing a custom inventory
  pipeline, not Shopify's built-in one.
{% endcomment %}
{%- assign variant = product.selected_or_first_available_variant -%}
{%- comment -%}
  .product__inventory sets `display: flex` unconditionally (see
  section-main-product.css), which overrides the `hidden` attribute's
  default `display: none` regardless of selector specificity - author
  CSS always wins over the browser's UA stylesheet. So visibility here
  is driven by the inline `display:none` starting style below, toggled
  via el.style.display in JS, not by the `hidden` attribute (kept only
  for its semantic/accessibility value, not for actually hiding this).
{%- endcomment -%}
<p
  class="product__inventory low-stock-alert"
  data-low-stock-alert
  data-variant-id="{{ variant.id }}"
  role="status"
  hidden
  style="display: none;"
>
  <svg width="15" height="15" aria-hidden="true">
    <circle cx="7.5" cy="7.5" r="7.5" fill="rgb(238,148,65,0.3)" />
    <circle cx="7.5" cy="7.5" r="5" stroke="rgb(255,255,255)" stroke-width="1" fill="rgb(238,148,65)" />
  </svg>
  Low stock — order soon!
</p>

{{ 'low-stock-alert.js' | asset_url | script_tag }}
